SIMPLE: thar
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thar
<hw>Thar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A
goatlike animal (<spn>Capra Jemlaica</spn>) native of the Himalayas. It
has small, flattened horns, curved directly backward. The hair of the
neck, shoulders, and chest of the male is very long, reaching to the
knees. Called also <altname>serow</altname>, and
<altname>imo</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>thaar</asp>, and
<asp>tahr</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thar
<hw>Thar</hw>, <pos>v. impersonal, pres.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thar</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧arf</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧earf</ets>,
infin. <ets>⟦thorn⟧urfan</ets> to need; akin to OHG. <ets>durfan</ets>,
G. <ets>d⟦uum⟧rfen</ets> to be allowed, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧urfa</ets> to
need, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧a⟦uacute⟧rban</ets>.]</ety> <def>It needs;
need.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>thar</qex> thee reck or care?</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tharms</ent>⟦br⟧
